habitat_description: The common yellowthroat occupies a wide range of habitats containing thick vegetation including wetlands, prairies and pine forests (Guzy and Ritchison 1999). Areas inhabited by the common yellowthroat include marshes, thickets near water, bogs, brushy pastures, old fields, and the undergrowth of humid forests (NatureServe 2009). However, a dense growth of vegetation appears to be more important in habitat selection than moisture or water (Guzy and Ritchison 1999). C. Maynard, 9feb10.
